===16â28 February===
The army stated on 17 February 2011 it would not field a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forexyard.com/en/news/Egypt-army-says-wont-field-presidential-candidate-2011-02-17T144839Z |title=Egypt army says won't field presidential candidate |publisher=Forexyard.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref> Four important figures of the former regime were detained on that day: former interior minister [[Habib el-Adly]], former minister of housing [[Ahmed Maghrabi]] and former tourism minister [[Zuheir Garana]], as well as steel tycoon [[Ahmed Ezz]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12500968 |title=BBC News - Egypt after Mubarak: Three ex-ministers arrested |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref>

=== 19â22 February ===
 
On 20 February, the constitutional reform committee announced its work was almost done,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90854/7293319.html |title=Egypt's constitutional amendments almost done: committee - People's Daily Online |publisher=English.people.com.cn |date=2011-02-20 |accessdate=2011-03-24}}</ref> and it was announced that the caretaker government would soon be reshuffled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90777/90854/7293328.html |title=Egyptian caretaker government to reshuffle soon: PM - People's Daily Online |publisher=English.people.com.cn |date=2011-02-20 |accessdate=2011-03-24}}</ref>

A government reshuffle took place on 22 February. The key ministries of defense, interior, foreign, finance and justice remained unchanged, however. New ministers included [[Yehia el-Gamal]] as deputy prime minister, the [[New Wafd Party]]'s [[Monir Fakhri Abdel Nour]] as tourism minister and the [[Tagammu Party]]'s [[Gowdat Abdel-Khaleq]] as minister of social solidarity and social justice, as well as [[Ismail Ibrahim Fahmy]] as the new labor minister. The changes were not well-received by the public, as most of Mubarak's former supporters remained in the cabinet, and there were renewed calls for a demonstration to demand the resignation of the interim government.<ref>{{cite web|author=By Reuters |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/international/egypt-swears-in-new-cabinet-retains-mubarak-era-ministers-1.345069 |title=Egypt swears in new cabinet, retains Mubarak-era ministers - Haaretz Daily Newspaper | Israel News |publisher=Haaretz.com |date=2011-03-20 |accessdate=2011-03-24}}</ref>
